              <h2>How to calculate GST in India</h2>
              <p>
                Goods and Services Tax (GST) in India is a destination-based
                indirect tax levied on the supply of goods and services. For
                most practical purposes, you either:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add GST</strong> to a base (taxable) value to get the
                  invoice value, or
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Remove GST</strong> from a GST-inclusive price to find
                  the base value and tax component.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Formula to add GST (exclusive → inclusive)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Given:</strong> Base value = \( V \), GST rate = \(
                  r\% \)
                </p>
                <p>GST amount:</p>
                <p>\[ \text{GST amount} = V \times \frac{r}{100} \]</p>
                <p>Invoice value (including GST):</p>
                <p>\[ \text{Invoice value} = V + \text{GST amount} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> Base value ₹1,000 at 18% GST</p>
              <ul>
                <li>GST amount = 1,000 × 18 ÷ 100 = ₹180</li>
                <li>Invoice value = 1,000 + 180 = <strong>₹1,180</strong></li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Formula to remove GST (inclusive → base)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Given:</strong> GST-inclusive value = \( G \), GST
                  rate = \( r\% \)
                </p>
                <p>Base value (before GST):</p>
                <p>\[ \text{Base value} = \frac{G}{1 + \frac{r}{100}} \]</p>
                <p>GST amount:</p>
                <p>\[ \text{GST amount} = G - \text{Base value} \]</p>
              </div>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> Inclusive price ₹1,180 at 18% GST</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Base value = 1,180 ÷ 1.18 ≈ ₹1,000</li>
                <li>GST amount = 1,180 − 1,000 = <strong>₹180</strong></li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. CGST, SGST and IGST split</h3>
              <p>
                The total GST rate is shared between the Centre and the States
                depending on whether the supply is intra-state or inter-state:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Intra-state supply</strong> (same State/UT): GST is
                  split into <strong>CGST</strong> and
                  <strong>SGST/UTGST</strong>, usually 50% each of the total
                  rate.
                  <br />
                  Example: 18% GST → 9% CGST + 9% SGST.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Inter-state supply</strong> (different States/UTs or
                  exports): GST is charged as <strong>IGST</strong> at the full
                  rate.
                  <br />
                  Example: 18% GST → 18% IGST.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically splits the tax into CGST + SGST or
                IGST based on the tax type you select.
              </p>

              <h2>GST slab rates in India</h2>
              <p>
                The GST Council notifies GST rates for goods and services.
                Broadly, the main slabs are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0%</strong> – Essential items, many food items,
                  exports (zero-rated), etc.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>5%</strong> – Essential goods and services (e.g.
                  certain food items, transport).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>12%</strong> – Standard goods/services in the
                  mid-range.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>18%</strong> – Most goods and services fall under this
                  slab.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>28%</strong> – Luxury goods and “sin” goods (e.g.
                  certain cars, tobacco products), often with additional cesses.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                There are also <strong>special rates</strong> such as
                <strong>0.1%</strong> and <strong>3%</strong> for specific
                categories (e.g. precious metals). Always refer to the latest
                notifications from the
                <a
                  href="https://cbic-gst.gov.in/gst-goods-services-rates.html"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >CBIC</a
                >
                for current rates.
              </p>

